File System in Node.js (fs module)

Node.js provides the fs (File System) module to:

Read files
Write files
Update files
Delete files
1. Import fs Module
const fs = require('fs');
2. Reading Files
(A) Asynchronous Read (Recommended)
fs.readFile('input.txt', 'utf8', (err, data) => {
    if (err) {
        console.log(err);
        return;
    }
    console.log(data);
});
Key Points:
Non-blocking
Suitable for backend applications
(B) Synchronous Read
const data = fs.readFileSync('input.txt', 'utf8');
console.log(data);
Key Points:
Blocking
Used for small scripts
3. Writing Files
(A) Asynchronous Write
fs.writeFile('output.txt', 'Hello World', (err) => {
    if (err) {
        console.log(err);
        return;
    }
    console.log("File written successfully");
});
(B) Synchronous Write
fs.writeFileSync('output.txt', 'Hello World');
4. Appending to File
fs.appendFile('output.txt', '\nNew Line', (err) => {
    if (err) throw err;
});
5. Modern Approach (Promises / Async-Await)
const fs = require('fs').promises;

async function run() {
    try {
        const data = await fs.readFile('input.txt', 'utf8');
        console.log(data);

        await fs.writeFile('output.txt', data + "\nProcessed");
    } catch (err) {
        console.log(err);
    }
}

run();
6. Working with JSON Files
Read JSON
const data = JSON.parse(fs.readFileSync('data.json', 'utf8'));
console.log(data);
Write JSON
fs.writeFileSync('data.json', JSON.stringify(data, null, 2));
7. Important Concepts
'utf8' → converts file data to string
Without encoding → returns Buffer
Always handle errors in async operations
8. Sync vs Async in File Handling
Operation	Sync	Async
Behavior	Blocking	Non-blocking
Performance	Slower	Faster
Usage	Small scripts	Real apps
9. Interview Definition

Reading and writing files in Node.js is done using the fs module, which provides both synchronous (blocking) and asynchronous (non-blocking) methods to handle file operations.

Final Summary
Use readFile and writeFile for async operations
Use readFileSync and writeFileSync for simple tasks
Prefer async or async/await in real applications
Handle errors properly
